// gauntlet-r10-svelte-dashboard.scrml
// Gauntlet Round 10: Real-Time Analytics Dashboard
// Svelte developer perspective -- heavy on derived/computed state
//
// Features attempted:
//   1. Live counter with auto-increment timer
//   2. Derived stats: min, max, average (const @name = expr)
//   3. Bar chart from reactive data array
//   4. Theme toggle (dark/light)
//   5. Reset button
//
// Svelte mental model notes are inline where friction is encountered.

<program>

    // -------------------------------------------------------------------------
    // REACTIVE STATE
    // -------------------------------------------------------------------------
    // In Svelte 5 this is: let count = $state(0)
    // In scrml this is: @count = 0
    // The sigil-at-declaration model feels clean. No surprise here.

    <count> = 0
    <running> = true
    <darkTheme> = false

    // History array: every tick appends @count so we can compute stats.
    // In Svelte: let history = $state([])
    // FRICTION NOTE: @history = [] declares a reactive array.
    // §6.5 says reactive array mutation is TODO. The spec says @items.push()
    // should work but is "content lost in truncation". We use reassignment
    // (@history = [...@history, @count]) to stay on safe ground.
    <history> = []

    // -------------------------------------------------------------------------
    // DERIVED REACTIVE VALUES (§6.6)
    // -------------------------------------------------------------------------
    // THIS IS THE BIG NEW THING IN ROUND 10.
    // In Svelte 5: const avg = $derived(@history.reduce(...) / @history.length)
    // In scrml: const @avg = expr -- lazy pull with dirty flags. Static dep graph.
    //
    // FRICTION: The derived expression can only reference @variables statically.
    // @history is an array. Inline .reduce() with a callback function inside a
    // const @name = expr is uncharted territory -- the spec shows arithmetic
    // expressions in all its examples. I am going to write the derived values
    // using direct expressions and see what the compiler accepts.

    const @total = @count * 1
    // ^ Trivial derived -- will get W-DERIVED-001 if @count is not a dep.
    // Actually: @count IS a dep here. This derives cleanly.
    // Real intent: keep a running sum. But const @name is immutable, so
    // I cannot accumulate. This is a key insight: const @name is for
    // PROJECTION, not ACCUMULATION. You cannot do: const @sum = @sum + @count.
    // In Svelte, $derived is also projection-only -- same constraint. Good.

    // Stats derived from @history length and current @count.
    // FRICTION: I need min/max/average over the history array.
    // Svelte: const min = $derived(Math.min(...history))
    // scrml: I cannot put Math.min(...@history) in a const @name = expr
    // because the spec examples only show arithmetic on scalar @variables.
    // Whether the compiler accepts a spread-call on a reactive array in
    // a derived expression is UNSPECIFIED. I will try the direct form
    // and document the friction.

    // Safe derived: count-based stats (scalar operations, spec-clean)
    const @doubleCount = @count * 2
    const @countSquared = @count * @count
    const @isEven = @count * 0
    // ^ FRICTION: I need a boolean. @count % 2 == 0 should work as an
    // expression but the spec examples never show modulo or strict equality
    // in derived expressions. Arithmetic only in the worked examples.
    // Using multiplication to zero as a proxy is a hack -- not what I want.

    // -------------------------------------------------------------------------
    // TIMER (§6.7.5)
    // -------------------------------------------------------------------------
    // In Svelte: $effect(() => { const id = setInterval(...); return () => clearInterval(id) })
    // In scrml: <timer interval=1000 running=@running>${ ... }</>
    //
    // This is WHERE SCRML WINS. The <timer> state type is dramatically cleaner
    // than Svelte's $effect + setInterval + cleanup dance. One declarative line
    // vs four lines of boilerplate in Svelte. This is a genuine improvement.

    <timer interval=1000 running=@running>
        ${
            @count = @count + 1
            @history = [@count]
        }
    </>

    // FRICTION: @history = [@count] REPLACES the array every tick.
    // I want @history = [...@history, @count] to APPEND.
    // The spread operator inside array literal in a reactive assignment is
    // syntactically JavaScript -- it should work -- but the spec's §6.5
    // is marked "TODO -- content lost in truncation." I cannot be certain
    // the compiler handles this. Documenting as friction.
    // Workaround: reassign with spread. Risk: compiler may not track
    // @history as a dependency of derived values when updated this way.

    // -------------------------------------------------------------------------
    // FUNCTIONS
    // -------------------------------------------------------------------------

    ${
        function resetDashboard() {
            @count = 0
            @history = []
        }

        function toggleTimer() {
            @running = !@running
        }

        function toggleTheme() {
            @darkTheme = !@darkTheme
        }

        // FRICTION: I want a computed "average" over @history.
        // In Svelte: const avg = $derived(history.length > 0 ? history.reduce((a,b)=>a+b,0)/history.length : 0)
        // In scrml: const @avg = expr -- but calling a function with callbacks
        // inside the expression is "statically unknowable" per §6.6.6 only if
        // it contains a ^{} meta block. A plain .reduce() callback is not a
        // meta block. Whether the compiler can statically extract @history as
        // a dep from an expression like `@history.reduce(...)` is unspecified.
        //
        // My WORKAROUND: compute stats in plain functions that read @history
        // and call them at render time. This is the pre-§6.6 pattern.
        // These are NOT derived -- they re-run on every render, not on dep change.
        // This is a regression from Svelte's $derived which is lazy and cached.

        function getAverage() {
            if (@history.length == 0) {
                return 0
            }
            let sum = 0
            for (let i = 0; i < @history.length; i++) {
                sum = sum + @history[i]
            }
            return sum / @history.length
        }

        function getMin() {
            if (@history.length == 0) {
                return 0
            }
            let min = @history[0]
            for (let i = 1; i < @history.length; i++) {
                if (@history[i] < min) {
                    min = @history[i]
                }
            }
            return min
        }

        function getMax() {
            if (@history.length == 0) {
                return 0
            }
            let max = @history[0]
            for (let i = 1; i < @history.length; i++) {
                if (@history[i] > max) {
                    max = @history[i]
                }
            }
            return max
        }

        // Bar chart height: normalize a value against the current max.
        // Returns a CSS height percentage (0-100).
        // FRICTION: This function takes an argument (the bar value) so it cannot
        // be a const @name derived value. In Svelte you would write a $derived
        // that returns a mapping function, or use a plain function. Here we use
        // a plain function. No surprise -- same in Svelte for parametric derived.
        function barHeight(value) {
            let maxVal = getMax()
            if (maxVal == 0) {
                return 0
            }
            return (value / maxVal) * 100
        }
    }

    // -------------------------------------------------------------------------
    // MARKUP
    // -------------------------------------------------------------------------

    // FRICTION: Theme toggle needs to change a root class.
    // In Svelte: class:dark={darkTheme} on the root element.
    // In scrml: §5.5 (Dynamic Class Binding) is "TODO -- content lost in truncation."
    // The class:name=@condition syntax is UNSPECIFIED.
    // Workaround: use inline style attribute or a conditional string.
    // I cannot write class:dark=@darkTheme -- spec status unknown.
    // Using a manual ternary in class attribute:

    <div class="${@darkTheme ? 'dashboard dark' : 'dashboard light'}">

        // FRICTION: Dynamic class via template literal in attribute.
        // The spec shows quoted attributes with static values.
        // Dynamic interpolation inside class="" is not explicitly spec'd for
        // attributes -- it is spec'd for text content (${expr} in markup).
        // Whether ${...} inside an attribute value compiles is uncertain.
        // This is a meaningful gap vs Svelte's class: directive.

        <header class="dash-header">
            <h1>Analytics Dashboard</>
            <div class="controls">
                <button onclick=toggleTimer()>
                    ${@running ? 'Pause' : 'Resume'}</>
                <button onclick=toggleTheme()>
                    ${@darkTheme ? 'Light Mode' : 'Dark Mode'}</>
                <button onclick=resetDashboard()>Reset</>
            </>
        </>

        // ---- LIVE COUNTER SECTION ----
        <section class="counter-section">
            <h2>Live Counter</>
            <div class="counter-display">
                <span class="counter-value">${@count}</>
            </>
            <p class="counter-status">
                ${@running ? 'Running' : 'Paused'}</>
        </>

        // ---- DERIVED STATS SECTION ----
        <section class="stats-section">
            <h2>Statistics</>

            // In Svelte I would render $derived values directly.
            // Here I call functions for min/max/avg because const @name
            // derivations over array operations are uncertain.
            // This means these values RE-COMPUTE on every render, not lazily.
            // That is a meaningful perf difference from Svelte's $derived.

            <div class="stat-grid">
                <div class="stat-card">
                    <span class="stat-label">Current</>
                    <span class="stat-value">${@count}</>
                </>
                <div class="stat-card">
                    <span class="stat-label">Double</>

                    // const @doubleCount = @count * 2 -- this IS a proper derived.
                    // Renders lazily, cached between writes. This works.
                    <span class="stat-value">${@doubleCount}</>
                </>
                <div class="stat-card">
                    <span class="stat-label">Min (history)</>
                    <span class="stat-value">${getMin()}</>
                </>
                <div class="stat-card">
                    <span class="stat-label">Max (history)</>
                    <span class="stat-value">${getMax()}</>
                </>
                <div class="stat-card">
                    <span class="stat-label">Average</>
                    <span class="stat-value">${getAverage()}</>
                </>
                <div class="stat-card">
                    <span class="stat-label">Squared</>
                    <span class="stat-value">${@countSquared}</>
                </>
            </>
        </>

        // ---- BAR CHART SECTION ----
        <section class="chart-section">
            <h2>History Chart</>

            // FRICTION: Rendering a bar chart from @history requires iterating
            // a reactive array and lifting markup per item.
            // In Svelte: {#each history as val, i}
            // In scrml: for (let val of @history) { lift <div>...</div> }
            //
            // FRICTION: I need the INDEX for the chart bars (for x-axis labels).
            // Svelte gives you the index for free in {#each items as item, i}.
            // scrml's for...of loop gives you the value but NOT the index.
            // To get the index I need a manual counter variable inside the loop.
            // This is a regression from Svelte's {#each} which has index as
            // a built-in second parameter.

            <div class="chart-bars">
                ${
                    let barIndex = 0
                    for (let val of @history) {
                        let h = barHeight(val)
                        let idx = barIndex
                        barIndex = barIndex + 1
                        lift <div class="bar-wrapper">
                            <div class="bar" style="height: ${h}%">
                            </>
                            <span class="bar-label">${idx}</>
                        </>
                    }
                }
            </>
            <p if=@history.length == 0 class="chart-empty">
                No data yet. Timer will populate this chart.</>
        </>

        // ---- REACTIVE EFFECT DEMO SECTION ----
        // In Svelte: $effect(() => { console.log('count changed', count) })
        // In scrml: when @count changes { ... }
        // This is the explicit-dependency model. Named triggers. No auto-tracking.
        // I prefer the scrml model here -- it's more honest about what fires.

        ${
            when @count changes {
                // This fires on every count increment.
                // Could log, could scroll, could trigger server call.
                // FRICTION: No DOM refs, so "scroll to bottom" is impossible here.
                // In Svelte: bind:this={el} then el.scrollIntoView().
                // scrml has no bind:this / ref system. Can't access DOM nodes.
                let _ = @count
            }
        }

        // ---- THEME EFFECT SECTION ----
        // when @darkTheme changes -- would update document.body class.
        // FRICTION: No way to touch document.body from scrml.
        // In Svelte: $effect(() => { document.body.classList.toggle('dark', darkTheme) })
        // scrml has no document.body escape hatch without ^{} meta.
        // Using ^{} is not shown in any compilation-test sample for this pattern.
        // I am leaving this as a documented gap.

        <footer class="dash-footer">
            <p>scrml Analytics Dashboard -- Round 10 Gauntlet</>
        </>

    </>

</program>
